cti-domain-research.skill — install this in Claude Code with the skill manager, or unzip and drop the folder into your skills directory.

Structure
cti-domain-research/
├── SKILL.md                    ← core skill (triggers in Claude.ai + Claude Code)
├── scripts/
│   ├── cti-search.md           ← /cti-search slash command for Claude Code
│   └── install.sh              ← one-shot installer
└── references/
    ├── domains.txt             ← 595 deduplicated domains from your list
    └── tier-map.json           ← authority scores + tier routing

Install (Claude Code)
bashunzip cti-domain-research.skill
bash cti-domain-research/scripts/install.sh

# Set your NotebookLM notebook ID
export NOTEBOOKLM_NOTEBOOK_ID=<your-id>

# Install the connector plugin if not already there
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/claude-code-zero /tmp/ccz
cp -r /tmp/ccz/plugins/notebooklm-connector ~/.claude/plugins/
cd ~/.claude/plugins/notebooklm-connector && npm install

Usage
bash/cti-search CVE-2024-21762
/cti-search LockBit ransomware --full --since 30
/cti-search ALPHV BlackCat --notebooklm
/cti-search supply chain npm --count 20 --tier 2 --notebooklm --notebook-id abc123
Tier routing logic: CVEs → T1 (CISA/NVD/MSRC) first; threat actors/malware → T2 (Unit42/Talos/Securelist); news/situational → T3 (Bleeping/Krebs/TheRecord); PoC/IOCs → T4 (any.run/VulnCheck/GreyNoise). The --notebooklm flag pipes all found URLs directly into your notebook via the notebooklm-connector plugin.